[{"nid":[{"value":1142}],"uuid":[{"value":"3481527f-0a05-4068-a9d3-ac9cb85449df"}],"vid":[{"value":3771}],"langcode":[{"value":"en"}],"type":[{"target_id":"page","target_type":"node_type","target_uuid":"17745858-15d2-4bcb-bc99-14fe05bb598b"}],"status":[{"value":true}],"title":[{"value":"Alderman Collections"}],"uid":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"439d086d-5c77-4435-8ce2-0d00e5f90bed","url":"\/user\/12"}],"created":[{"value":1519757142}],"changed":[{"value":1520535580}],"promote":[{"value":false}],"sticky":[{"value":false}],"revision_timestamp":[{"value":1520535580}],"revision_uid":[{"target_id":29,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"6a90bc39-8567-443e-9726-9ea9be8145fa","url":"\/user\/29"}],"revision_log":[],"revision_translation_affected":[{"value":true}],"default_langcode":[{"value":true}],"path":[],"publish_on":[],"unpublish_on":[],"body":[{"value":" \u003Cp\u003EWhen planning began for the new Alderman Library the collection was about a quarter-million books, with growth capacity to accommodate 600,000 books. By the time the Library opened in 1938 the print collection was over three-hundred thousand books. Today the collection has increased to its current size of 2.5 million items\u2014about half of the total collections held by the University libraries, excluding Archives and Special Collections. The largest subject areas of the Alderman book collection are in the following call number areas:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch3\u003EMakeup of Alderman Collections\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Ctable class=\u0022aldCollectionTable\u0022\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022col\u0022 width=\u002240%\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubject Area\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/th\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022col\u0022 width=\u002230%\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECall Number\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/th\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022col\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercentage of Alderman\u0026rsquo;s   Collection\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/th\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003ELanguage, Literature, and Bibliography\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EP and Z\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E21%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003EWorld and U.S. History\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EC, D, E, F, and G\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E15%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003ESocial Sciences\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EH\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E8%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003EPhilosophy, Psychology, and Religion\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EB\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E8%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003EPolitical Science and Law\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EJ and K\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E4%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003EEducation\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EL\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E1%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003EGeneral\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003EA\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E1%\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003Ctr\u003E\r\n\u003Cth scope=\u0022row\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETOTAL BOOKS\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026nbsp;\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003Ctd\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E58%\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/td\u003E\r\n\u003C\/tr\u003E\r\n\u003C\/table\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAbout 60% of Alderman\u0026rsquo;s collection is in book format and uses the Library of Congress (LC) classification scheme, as indicated above. The remainder of the collection, approximately 40%, are US and Virginia government documents, newspapers, microforms, maps, and other materials. All the items in the collection were selected by librarians from state and local funds, given as gifts, requested by members of the UVA community, or provided to us as a U.S. depository library. \u003Cbr \/\u003E\r\n  The goal, since Alderman Library opened, has been to create an academic collection that meets the research and teaching needs of our faculty and students. Those needs change over time, and the collection reflects that evolution, over nearly a century. \u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Ch2\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe Collection During the Renovation\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe Alderman Library collection needs to be removed from the building before renovation begins. The strategy for managing the collection during renovation, approximately five years, involves doubling the capacity at Ivy Stacks and installing compact shelving on the first floor of Clemons Library. \u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003EBooks that will be provided from Clemons will include high-use materials from every subject area of the Alderman and Clemons print book collection. This will provide a browsable collection of at least 500,000 items immediately retrievable from compact shelving by library users, with room for five years of growth in the print collections.  \u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003Cli\u003EThe remainder of the materials from Alderman will move to Ivy Stacks, where print materials are shelved in preservation-quality environmental conditions.  During the renovation, these materials can be retrieved in the same way users now retrieve Ivy Stacks materials.  In order to increase efficiency in using this collection, any items retrieved from Ivy Stacks during renovation will be reshelved with the browsable collection in Clemons.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe Collection in the Renovated Alderman Library \u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWe expect that a renovated Alderman Library will be beautiful and safe, and will meet the needs of all the Library\u0026rsquo;s users.  It will house substantial print collections throughout the building, with the highest concentration of books in the areas of new construction.   When we have finalized floor plans and have determined, in conversation with library users, the tolerance for compact shelving and the criteria we will use to select the collections that return to Alderman from Ivy Stacks and from Clemons, we will be able to specify the number of items that will be in Alderman Library post-renovation.  We expect those collections will be more deliberately curated, easier to find and use, and better preserved than ever before.  \u003C\/p\u003E","format":"full_html","summary":""}],"field_parent_page":[{"target_id":836,"target_type":"node","target_uuid":"a20f0a27-7bde-48ec-aac5-8e55292158a8","url":"\/node\/836"}],"field_path":[{"value":"\/renovation\/alderman-collections\/"}],"field_serve_via_iframe":[{"value":false}],"field_sidebar":[],"field_subnav":[{"target_id":13,"target_type":"block_content","target_uuid":"ef8c99f5-9638-461a-98d5-f3250127ff9c","url":"\/block\/13"}],"field_upload_a_file":[]},{"nid":[{"value":1141}],"uuid":[{"value":"707ae517-a3c1-4618-83fa-74c19f26be47"}],"vid":[{"value":3343}],"langcode":[{"value":"en"}],"type":[{"target_id":"page","target_type":"node_type","target_uuid":"17745858-15d2-4bcb-bc99-14fe05bb598b"}],"status":[{"value":true}],"title":[{"value":"History of the Project"}],"uid":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"439d086d-5c77-4435-8ce2-0d00e5f90bed","url":"\/user\/12"}],"created":[{"value":1519756992}],"changed":[{"value":1519757121}],"promote":[{"value":false}],"sticky":[{"value":false}],"revision_timestamp":[{"value":1519757121}],"revision_uid":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"439d086d-5c77-4435-8ce2-0d00e5f90bed","url":"\/user\/12"}],"revision_log":[],"revision_translation_affected":[{"value":true}],"default_langcode":[{"value":true}],"path":[],"publish_on":[],"unpublish_on":[],"body":[{"value":"\u003Ch3\u003EAnother step on the Library\u2019s rich journey\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022A tall circular room with books and studying spaces.\u0022 data-align=\u0022right\u0022 data-caption=\u0022The Dome Room, shown here during its days as the University Library, occupies the center of UVA\u2019s Rotunda.\u0022 data-entity-type=\u0022file\u0022 data-entity-uuid=\u0022d2ac5b0d-d020-46b9-8a36-d036f93aa493\u0022 height=\u0022286\u0022 src=\u0022\/sites\/default\/files\/inline-images\/DomeRoomEdit.jpg\u0022 width=\u0022359\u0022 \/\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe history of the University of Virginia can be divided into three chapters, each marked by the construction of a library.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch4\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe Rotunda\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h4\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe first chapter was the building of the Rotunda, the first library at UVA. Unlike other universities of its era, the University of Virginia was built around a library, rather than a chapel or other religious structure. This was symbolic of the central importance of knowledge to this university, and Thomas Jefferson himself was deeply engaged in selecting the materials that made up that library\u2019s original collection, and in developing the system by which it would be organized. The Rotunda served as the University Library for over 100 years, until collections needs outgrew the Rotunda\u0027s capacity.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch4\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlderman Library\u003C\/strong\u003E\u003C\/h4\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe building of Alderman Library, in 1937, marked the second important chapter of UVA\u2019s history, as it was a response to the faculty\u2019s demand for the volume and type of current information necessary to function as a research university. At the same time that Alderman Library was built, the University committed to a very significant increase in annual spending on collections. Those collections, in turn, were housed in the Alderman stacks. Originally closed to most patrons, these stacks were laid out to maximize the storage of printed matter, and the stacks themselves were part of a state-of-the art integrated book storage system (the Snead Book Distributor) that included a book conveyor belt. Librarians picked requested titles from the shelves and dropped them on the belt, and they were delivered to the circulation desk.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022Three historic photos of Alderman Library\u0022 data-align=\u0022center\u0022 data-caption=\u0022Left to right: Back of Alderman Library before construction of the \u201cNew Stacks\u201d in the 1960s, construction of \u201cNew Stacks\u201d, Alderman\u2019s original layout from above.\u0022 data-entity-type=\u0022file\u0022 data-entity-uuid=\u0022b36589a4-b77d-4c0b-b627-ab6152cb01a0\u0022 src=\u0022\/sites\/default\/files\/inline-images\/historic-photos-1024x334.jpg\u0022 \/\u003E\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe renovation of Alderman, beginning in 2018, marks the third chapter in the University\u2019s history, and the choices we make in that renovation will say a great deal about what we think the future of research and scholarship will be, as well as what we think a great university needs in order to support those activities.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EWe also need to replace the plumbing. The systems in Alderman Library\u2014the plumbing, as well as the wiring, the heating and air conditioning\u2014are at the point of failure. Some of these systems are original to the building and are approaching 80 years of operation. Frequent fire alarms (and building evacuations) are the result of small failures in these systems, but they are also a reminder that there is no fire suppression in the building\u2014no sprinkler systems in those (now open) stacks full of paper. The collections are at risk, but there are also real life-safety issues throughout the building, and these must be addressed.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe general plan is to maintain the building\u2019s character and its shell, and replace the interior with new construction having LEED-quality systems and housing collections and services that will support the University\u0027s mission in its third century. New construction opening onto University Avenue will be the face of a Library that is sustainable and future-oriented, with elements of architectural diversity that respect the past, but are designed to accommodate change. We expect that the whole of a renovated Alderman will keep the large windows, the high ceilings, and the contemplative character that all of us enjoy in the original building.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAcademic libraries serve multiple purposes for multiple constituencies, and we will work diligently with the University community to understand and balance those needs. Students, faculty, and library staff are all deeply vested in getting this balance right, and producing a building that allows for growth in collections, for the evolution of knowledge, and for change over time, as the building learns from its users. The expansion of Ivy Stacks, happening in the summer of 2017, is a key precursor of this project, as it will allow the temporary off-site storage of the 2.5M items in the Alderman collection, with new preservation-quality HVAC. But browsing collections will return to Alderman, and the new building, like the Rotunda before it, will reflect thoughtful organization of resources, interspersed with space to use those resources. And, like Alderman today, the new building will offer many different environments for study\u2014from bookish spaces like the McGregor Room to spaces organized around other kinds of information or for other purposes, allowing for quiet study, group study, and social interaction.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n","format":"basic_html","summary":""}],"field_parent_page":[{"target_id":836,"target_type":"node","target_uuid":"a20f0a27-7bde-48ec-aac5-8e55292158a8","url":"\/node\/836"}],"field_path":[{"value":"\/renovation\/history-of-the-project\/"}],"field_serve_via_iframe":[],"field_sidebar":[],"field_subnav":[{"target_id":13,"target_type":"block_content","target_uuid":"ef8c99f5-9638-461a-98d5-f3250127ff9c","url":"\/block\/13"}],"field_upload_a_file":[]},{"nid":[{"value":1140}],"uuid":[{"value":"c42f956c-c524-42c7-aa86-3f0c9bb28f69"}],"vid":[{"value":3576}],"langcode":[{"value":"en"}],"type":[{"target_id":"page","target_type":"node_type","target_uuid":"17745858-15d2-4bcb-bc99-14fe05bb598b"}],"status":[{"value":true}],"title":[{"value":"Project Planning \u0026 Documents"}],"uid":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"439d086d-5c77-4435-8ce2-0d00e5f90bed","url":"\/user\/12"}],"created":[{"value":1519756411}],"changed":[{"value":1520031661}],"promote":[{"value":false}],"sticky":[{"value":false}],"revision_timestamp":[{"value":1520031661}],"revision_uid":[{"target_id":29,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"6a90bc39-8567-443e-9726-9ea9be8145fa","url":"\/user\/29"}],"revision_log":[],"revision_translation_affected":[{"value":true}],"default_langcode":[{"value":true}],"path":[],"publish_on":[],"unpublish_on":[],"body":[{"value":"\u003Cp\u003EOn April 20, 2016, the Virginia legislature passed House Bill 1344, a capital projects funding bill that approved funding for a planning study to: \u201cRenovate Alderman Library, Life Safety Phase I.\u201d \u0026nbsp;The focus is on fire, safety, and system renewals of the building, although there is also some acknowledgment that mission update and modernization is included.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EAnticipated timeline and list of relevant documents can be found below.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch2 id=\u0022timeline\u0022\u003ERenovation Timeline\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ctable id=\u0022renovation-timeline\u0022\u003E\r\n  \u003Ctr\u003E\r\n    \u003Cth scope=\u0022col\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ELibrary Project\u003C\/span\u003E\u003C\/th\u003E\r\n    \u003Ct