te.\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/guides.lib.virginia.edu\/subjectlibrarians\u0022\u003EConsult with a\u0026nbsp;library\u0026nbsp;liaison\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/data.library.virginia.edu\/\u0022\u003EConsult with a data expert\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch2\u003EPublication and Scholarly Communication Services\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/libra.virginia.edu\/\u0022\u003ELibra: Online Archive of University of Virginia Scholarship\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/www.hsl.virginia.edu\/portal\/researcher\/public_access.cfm\u0022\u003EAccess Requirements for NIH-Funded Research\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/copyright.library.virginia.edu\/\u0022\u003ECopyright and Scholarly Communication Resources\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/guides.lib.virginia.edu\/citations\u0022\u003ECitation Analysis\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch2\u003EInstruction Services\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/services\/course-reserves\/\u0022\u003EPlace Course Materials on Reserve\u003C\/a\u003E\u003Cbr \/\u003E\r\n\tPlace books and videos on reserve in a library and request that materials be scanned for UVaCollab.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003ERequest Course-Related Library Instruction\u003Cbr \/\u003E\r\n\t\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/guides.lib.virginia.edu\/subjectlibrarians\u0022\u003ESubject librarian\u003C\/a\u003E\u0026nbsp;liaisons will arrange instruction for individual classes.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch2\u003EDigital Services\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/libraries\/#scholars-lab\u0022\u003EScholars\u2019 Lab\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/libraries\/#robertson-media-center\u0022\u003ERobertson Media Center\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/services\/digitization\/\u0022\u003EDigitization and Media Creation Services\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/dmconsult.library.virginia.edu\/\u0022\u003EData Management\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/statlab.library.virginia.edu\/\u0022\u003EStatLab \u2013 Statistical Consulting\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022http:\/\/guides.lib.virginia.edu\/data\u0022\u003EData Acquisition \u0026amp; Discovery\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n","format":"basic_html","summary":""}],"field_parent_page":[{"target_id":1107,"target_type":"node","target_uuid":"8d40f2c4-6a70-4e17-b1c2-7984b32909ac","url":"\/node\/1107"}],"field_path":[{"value":"\/services\/faculty\/"}],"field_serve_via_iframe":[{"value":false}],"field_sidebar":[{"target_id":22,"target_type":"block_content","target_uuid":"c887f2a1-7310-4716-a722-0f228dd2b5eb","url":"\/block\/22"}],"field_subnav":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"block_content","target_uuid":"14584a3a-78c5-4512-ba65-6c2524cf3776","url":"\/block\/12"}],"field_upload_a_file":[]},{"nid":[{"value":711}],"uuid":[{"value":"67895b73-bfc2-4f4f-9d54-849fec13708e"}],"vid":[{"value":3953}],"langcode":[{"value":"en"}],"type":[{"target_id":"page","target_type":"node_type","target_uuid":"17745858-15d2-4bcb-bc99-14fe05bb598b"}],"status":[{"value":true}],"title":[{"value":"University Library Course Enrichment Grants \u00a0"}],"uid":[{"target_id":12,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"439d086d-5c77-4435-8ce2-0d00e5f90bed","url":"\/user\/12"}],"created":[{"value":1497644217}],"changed":[{"value":1521689918}],"promote":[{"value":false}],"sticky":[{"value":false}],"revision_timestamp":[{"value":1521689918}],"revision_uid":[{"target_id":22,"target_type":"user","target_uuid":"0da2c5ee-4a8f-40a4-9b16-d3a48431aed1","url":"\/user\/22"}],"revision_log":[],"revision_translation_affected":[{"value":true}],"default_langcode":[{"value":true}],"path":[],"publish_on":[],"unpublish_on":[],"body":[{"value":"\u003Cp\u003EThe University of Virginia Library is pleased to offer Course Enrichment Grants for faculty who want to enhance students\u2019 abilities to seek, evaluate, and use information and data in scholarly contexts, as well as create new types of media-rich class assignments.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFaculty recipients of these grants will be awarded:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul type=\u0022disc\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E$2500, which can be applied either as a summer salary or to research accounts;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EDedicated support from experienced librarians, technologists, or other library staff;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EParticipation in a learning community.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch2\u003EThis year\u2019s Enrichment Grants will cover three areas: Information Literacy, Data Literacy, and Digital Literacy\u003C\/h2\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInformation Literacy:\u003C\/strong\u003E \u0026nbsp;enhance students\u2019 ability to critically understand and use information both within and outside their field of study.\r\n\r\n\t\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty participating in this program will partner with a team of librarians to align information literacy skills with course content and pedagogical goals. The librarians will include subject and pedagogy experts, as well as others relevant to the purpose of the grant (e.g., intellectual property or metadata experts). Students in the course will gain skills and experiences that encourage them to effectively find, evaluate, manage, and use information. For example: \u0026nbsp;\r\n\t\t\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EEnglish Writing students examine how popular and scholarly sources differ in terms of a singular global event over the course of 5-10 years. Students journal their perceptions throughout the course and showcase their findings in a culminating project. \u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EChemistry students collate articles related to weekly topics and assess for appropriateness for target audience, research design, data quality, and contributions to the cycle of scholarship. The culminating project is a NSF-style research grant.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EData Literacy:\u003C\/strong\u003E strengthen students\u2019 ability to critically engage in society through data.\r\n\t\u003Cul type=\u0022circle\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty participating in this program will help their students develop data competencies, which are essential among students and researchers across disciplinary boundaries, professionals working in all sectors, and citizens engaged in an increasingly data-driven world. With a grounding in data literacy, students will be able to: discover\u0026nbsp;reliable data sources, whether public, open, licensed, or internally generated; ethically use data, including understanding the rights and responsibilities of data reuse and the ethical handling, storage, and citation of data; and collect data with an emphasis on reproducibility, including documentation of instruments and protocols, along with appropriate file formats, organization, storage, and consideration of sharing and archiving data where appropriate. For example: \u0026nbsp;\r\n\t\t\u003Cul type=\u0022square\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EReligious Studies students examine surveys of religious life utilizing a religion-focused data archive. Students will be able to draw conclusions from the data. The culminating project is a visualization of identified trends. \u0026nbsp;\u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EPolitics students utilize open data to examine civic engagement in Charlottesville. Students learn about ethical data re-use and implement reproducible methods to analyze the data.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigital Literacy: \u003C\/strong\u003E\u0026nbsp;infuse innovative technologies such as virtual reality, video production, and 3D printing into courses to enable student engagement with new forms of academic scholarship while producing meaningful learning objects.\r\n\t\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty participating in this program will partner with media technologists, instructional designers, and, where appropriate, intellectual property experts to support innovative uses of video, 3D and immersive technologies, media visualization, and maker-related activities. For example:\r\n\t\t\u003Cul\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EEngineering students use 3D modeling to create and then print prototypes of their inventions as part of an entrepreneurship course. \u0026nbsp;\u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EHistory students can learn to marry storyboarding with skillful video and audio techniques to produce short films.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EArchaeology students use 3D scanning to recreate an artifact that can be examined and handled for further study. \u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\t\u003Cli\u003EArt\/design students use virtual reality to closely study pieces of rare or inaccessible artwork. Students may then use 3D modeling to print the piece.\u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\t\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch3\u003EWho is eligible for the grant? What are the selection criteria? How do I apply?\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EFull or part-time faculty in all disciplines who are teaching semester-long courses are encouraged to apply for Course Enrichment Grants.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe grant deadline is 4\/13\/2018. \u0026nbsp;Notifications will be made by 4\/20\/2018.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EThe library will award as many as eight grants of $2500 each.\u003Cbr \/\u003E\r\nCriteria for selection include depth of the proposed improvements to the course, potential for partnership building, use of innovative pedagogy or technologies, and feasibility in terms of library staff availability.\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/services\/faculty\/information-literacy-grant\/application\u0022\u003E\u003Cpaper-button raised=\u0022\u0022\u003EApply Now\u003C\/paper-button\u003E\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch3\u003EWhat happens after a grant is awarded?\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul type=\u0022disc\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty and librarians, educational technologists or other appropriate library staff will meet regularly to design a course that incorporates the creative, research and evaluative skills students need at the level and in the discipline for that course. \u0026nbsp;The team will examine class readings, assignments, learning outcomes, and core competencies, and will create opportunities within the course for reflective discovery of information, the examination of the production and value of information, and the use of information in creating new forms of work and in participating ethically in communities of learning.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Ch3\u003EExpectations\u003C\/h3\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul type=\u0022disc\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFor Fall 2018 courses, work will occur in the summer with an expected completion of a syllabus with revised course outcomes by August 15, 2018. For Spring 2019 courses, work will occur during the\u0026nbsp;summer or fall,\u0026nbsp;with the expected completion of a revised syllabus by December 2, 2018.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty will meet with their assigned librarian\/library team at least three times before their respective deadline to discuss curricular changes.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty will include at least one library team member on the course Collab site. \u0026nbsp;\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty will participate in a forum organized by the Library where faculty members and librarians discuss their experiences incorporating new literacies into their teaching.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003EFaculty will\u0026nbsp;write a brief overview of their course, highlighting changes brought about by the grant, for Library documentation of the Course Enrichment Program.\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003EIf you have further questions about the grant, please email Judith Thomas, \u003Ca href=\u0022mailto:jet3h@virginia.edu\u0022\u003Ejet3h@virginia.edu\u003C\/a\u003E.\u003Cbr \/\u003E\r\nGeneral Library Contact Information:\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cul type=\u0022disc\u0022\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E(434) 924-3021\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022mailto:library@virginia.edu\u0022\u003Elibrary@virginia.edu\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\t\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/askalibrarian\/\u0022\u003EAsk a Librarian\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/li\u003E\r\n\u003C\/ul\u003E\r\n\r\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022\/services\/faculty\/information-literacy-grant\/application\u0022\u003E\u003Cpaper-button raised=\u0022\u0022\u003EApply Now\u003C\/paper-button\u003E\u003C\/a\u003E\u003C\/p\u003E\r\n","format":"basic_html","summary":""}],"field_parent_page":[{"target_id":714,"target_type":"node","target_uuid":"0151313f-af54-4344-8569-88529369afd1","url":"\/node\/714"}],"field_path":[{"value":"\/services\/faculty\/information-literacy-grant\/"}],"field_serve_via_iframe":[{"value":false}],"field_sidebar":[],"field_subnav":[],"field_upload_a_file":[]},{"nid":[{"value":710}],"